<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Margin-of-error-95.svg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f=
/f9/Margin-of-error-95.svg/500px-Margin-of-error-95.svg.png" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"350" height=3D"285" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"575" data-file-height=3D"469"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Probability_density_function" title=3D"Probability density =
function">Probability densities</a> of polls of different sizes, each color=
-coded to its 95% <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_inter=
val" title=3D"Confidence interval">confidence interval</a>  (below), margin=
 of error (left), and sample size (right). Each interval reflects the range=
 within which one may have 95% confidence that the <i>true</i> percentage m=
ay be found, given a reported percentage of 50%. The <i>margin of error</i>=
 is half the confidence interval (also, the <i>radius</i> of the interval).=
 The larger the sample, the smaller the margin of error. Also, the further =
from 50% the reported percentage, the smaller the margin of error.</figcapt=
ion></figure>
<p>The <b>margin of error</b> is a statistic expressing the amount of rando=
m <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_error" title=3D"Samplin=
g error">sampling error</a> in the results of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistical_survey" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistica=
l survey">survey</a>. The larger the margin of error, the less confidence o=
ne should have that a poll result would reflect the result of a simultaneou=
s census of the entire <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical=
_population" title=3D"Statistical population">population</a>. The margin of=
 error will be positive whenever a population is incompletely sampled and t=
he outcome measure has positive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Va=
riance" title=3D"Variance">variance</a>, which is to say, whenever the meas=
ure <i>varies</i>.
</p><p>The term <i>margin of error</i> is often used in non-survey contexts=
 to indicate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observational_error" =
title=3D"Observational error">observational error</a> in reporting measured=
 quantities.
</p>
